-- South African Stocks Rise, Led By Anglo, BJM, BHP, FirstRand and Impala
-- Garth Theunissen
-- 2010-06-21T10:27:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/south-african-stocks-gain-led-higher-by-anglo-bjm-impala-sasol-telkom.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  advanced 346.51, or 1.3 percent, to 28,108.21 by
12:16 p.m. in Johannesburg.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up more than 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark
stock index, rose 6.61 rand, or 2.2 percent, to 303.44 rand.
Copper climbed the most in a month after China signaled it would
allow its currency to strengthen against the dollar, boosting
speculation a stronger yuan may increase imports of industrial
metals to the world’s largest consumer. Shares in larger rival
 BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ) advanced 7.34 rand, or 3.4 percent, to
224.19 rand.  
 Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s biggest producer
of the metal, rallied 17.60 rand, or 2.2 percent, to 815.60
rand. Platinum increased as much as 1.3 percent to $1,608.25 an
ounce, the highest since May 20.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. 
(IMP SJ), the world’s second-largest producer of the metal, rose
6.88 rand, or 3.6 percent, to 199.04 rand, the highest since May
13.  
 Barnard Jacobs Mellet Holdings Ltd.  (BJM SJ), the brokerage
that last month agreed to sell its securities unit to
Renaissance Capital, jumped 52 cents, or 14 percent, to 4.33
rand, the highest since April 2, 2008. BJM, as the company is
known, said  FirstRand Ltd.  offered to buy the company for 4.50
rand a share.  
 FirstRand (FSR SJ), South Africa’s second-biggest banking
group, rose 32 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 19.27 rand.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, advanced 6.15 rand, or 2.2 percent, to 291.85
rand. Oil rallied for a second day, gaining as much as 2.2
percent to $78.87 a barrel.  
 Telkom South Africa Ltd.  (TKG SJ), Africa’s largest fixed-
line phone company, rose 1.01 rand, or 2.7 percent, to 37.91
rand. Telkom said it may sell all or part of its Nigerian
business.  
